Hi Prof. Quilici,

I have written a average-array plan, 

'("ave-array-template"
  (
    (e1 (Assign Id1 Id2))               ;mean = 0
    (e2 (Assign Id3 Id4))               ;i = 0
    (e3 (Less Id5 Id6 Id7))             ;i<n
    (e4 (Index Id7 Id8 Id9))            ;a[i] --Id9
    (e5 (PlusAssign Id10 Id11))         ;mean += Id9
    (e6 (Plus Id12 Id13 Id14))          ;i++ ==> Id14 = i + 1
    (e7 (Assign Id15 Id16))             ;i = Id14
    (e8 (DivAssign Id17 Id18))          ;mean /= n
  )
  (
    (equal-zero (e1) Id2)
    (equal-one (e6) Id13)  
    (data-dependency (e5 e1) Id10)
    (data-dependency (e3 e2) Id5 )
    (data-dependency (e3 e7) Id5)
    (data-dependency (e7 e6) Id16) 
    (data-dependency (e5 e4) Id11) 
    (same-data-dependency (e4 e3) (Id8 Id5))
    (same-data-dependency (e7 e3) (Id15 Id5)) 
    (same-data-dependency (e3 e8) (Id6 Id18))
    (data-dependency (e8 e1) Id17)
    (data-dependency (e8 e5) Id17) 
  )
 )

(data-dependency (e-i e-j) Id )
means component e-i's data Id is set at component e-j;

(same-data-dependency (e-i e-j) (Id-i Id-j))
means the data Id-i used in component e-i and the data Id-j used
in component e-j have the same dependency. Such as the n in the plan
is not changed and dependency of n won't change.

Notice that the i in the loop is dependent on both the forinit and forincre
and the mean in (DivAssign mean n) is dependent on both mean=0 and mean += a[i].

